{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Time Delay by Distance\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Delays a stereo or mono track by distance based on the approximate speed of sound through air at room temperature. This is a rough approximation of the speed of sound and should be pretty close enough for normal recording conditions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Select your preferred units.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Set the distance to delay the audio.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a Gain plugin with a VU meter and a feature to automatically match the output volume to a target level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Gain - Allows you to manually change the gain.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Target Level - This is the level you want your volume level to be at. This will be a target for gain matching as well as a target for the 0 on the VU meter so that you can match the level manually. By default this is set to the standard -18db.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Gain Match - When you slide this over, it will set the gain so that the output level matches the target level and then it will immediately switch off.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 VU Speed - This is the speed/response of the VU meter\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To achieve the most accurate results, set the gain to 0db and play/loop your track at its busiest/loudest point when you Gain Match. If the result isn't quite right, it may be because you matched if on significant dip/peak. You can set the Gain back to 0 and try again. Or if the result is just a little bit off, you can adjust the gain accordingly and watch the VU meter for reference to your Target level.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inline Input Viewer shows you the incomming waveform and midi data and is used as embedded view in the mcp.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 LMB: switch between mono and stereo view RMB: switch between midi and Audioview\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Within the script you can Change a few Options:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 -Clip hold Time -Waveform Time Zoom (how much you see of the waveform at the same time) -Clear Color (Background Color of the FX to match your theme.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
